Attorney General John Ashcroft was cleared of violating anti-lobbying laws for promoting the Patriot Act in speeches.
The Act, passed after 9/11, expanded law enforcement powers against terrorists.
President Bush praised Ashcroft's efforts in enhancing national security.
However, critics argue the Act infringes on civil liberties.
A coalition, including the ACLU and conservative groups, seeks to repeal certain provisions.
The debate over renewing the Patriot Act highlights the delicate balance between security and freedom.
Some argue for amendments to protect privacy rights while maintaining effective counterterrorism measures.
The future of the Act remains contentious, with calls for increased oversight and safeguards.
